studyDesigns.name: Study Design
studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: LY900018 3 mg (Nasal Glucagon)
arms.description: Single 3-mg dose of LY900018 administered nasally by study site personnel

arms.name: IMG 1 mg (Intramuscular Glucagon)
arms.description: Single 1-mg dose of GlucaGen administered by intramuscular injection by study site personnel

studyCohorts.name: Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus (T1DM)
studyCohorts.characteristic: Japanese patients with T1DM on daily insulin therapy for at least 1 year

studyCohorts.name: Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM)
studyCohorts.characteristic: Japanese patients with T2DM on daily insulin therapy with or without oral anti-hyperglycemic medications for at least 1 year

eligibilityCriteria.name: Unstable insulin regimen or blood glucose control exclusion
Severe hypoglycemia or loss of consciousness history exclusion
Epilepsy or seizure disorder history exclusion

objectives.name: Primary Efficacy Objective
objectives.text: To demonstrate that 3 mg LY900018 is non-inferior to 1 mg IMG for the proportion of patients achieving treatment success from insulin-induced hypoglycemia using a non-inferiority margin of 10%

objectives.name: Safety and Tolerability Objective
objectives.text: To compare the safety and tolerability of 3 mg LY900018 with 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Pharmacokinetic Objective
objectives.text: To characterize the PK profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Pharmacodynamic Objective
objectives.text: To characterize the PD profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

endpoints.name: Treatment Success Rate
endpoints.text: The proportion of patients achieving treatment success defined as either an increase in PG to >70 mg/dL or an increase of >20 mg/dL from nadir within 30 minutes after administration of glucagon. The nadir is defined as the minimum PG value at the time of or within 10 minutes following glucagon administration.

endpoints.name: Safety and Tolerability Endpoints
endpoints.text: SAE, TEAEs (including gastrointestinal, nasal, and non-nasal AEs), vital signs

endpoints.name: Pharmacokinetic Parameters
endpoints.text: PK parameters include AUC, Cmax, Tmax

endpoints.name: Pharmacodynamic Parameters
endpoints.text: PD parameters include BGmax and Tmax

studyInterventions.name: LY900018
studyInterventions.description: Nasal glucagon powder formulation for rescue treatment of hypoglycemia, synthetic single-chain 29-amino-acid polypeptide identical to human glucagon

studyInterventions.name: GlucaGen
studyInterventions.description: Intramuscular glucagon injection, currently approved product requiring reconstitution prior to administration

studyInterventions.name: Human Regular Insulin
studyInterventions.description: IV infusion used to induce hypoglycemia during the study procedure

encounters.name: Within 282 days after last study treatment

activities.name: Informed Consent
activities.description: Informed Consent

activities.name: Randomization
activities.description: Randomization

activities.name: Admission to CRU
activities.description: Admission to CRU. Admission can be rescheduled if PG level is not 90 to 250 mg/dL on Day 1.

activities.name: Discharge from CRU
activities.description: Discharge from CRU. Patient may be discharged 6 hours after glucagon administration. A patient may remain inpatient at the CRU at the discretion of the investigator.

activities.name: Medical History
activities.description: Medical History

activities.name: Collect Pre-existing Conditions and Adverse Events
activities.description: Collect Pre-existing Conditions and Adverse Events

activities.name: Physical Exam
activities.description: Physical Exam. After screening, medical assessment only performed to include medical review and targeted examination, as appropriate.

activities.name: Height and Weight
activities.description: Height and Weight. Height is at screening only. Weight on Day 1 will be collected before the start of the procedure to induce hypoglycemia.

activities.name: Collect Hypoglycemic Events
activities.description: Collect Hypoglycemic Events. Refer to Section 9.5.5.1.

activities.name: Collect Concomitant Medications
activities.description: Collect Concomitant Medications. Review patients' insulin regimens to confirm acceptability to undergo the procedure to induce hypoglycemia.

activities.name: Meal
activities.description: Meal. After completion of all PK sampling, patients will be provided a carbohydrate-rich meal. The investigator will ensure the patient's PG is stable. A prandial insulin dose will be administered if needed.

activities.name: Insulin infusion to Induce Hypoglycemia
activities.description: Insulin infusion to Induce Hypoglycemia. Procedures in Period 2 will occur at approximately the same time as those in Period 1. Insulin infusion is stopped once bedside PG is <60 mg/dL.

activities.name: Bedside PG Monitoring for Safety
activities.description: Bedside PG Monitoring for Safety. Samples will be collected during the hypoglycemia induction procedure and post study treatment (up to 120 mins). Bedside PG monitoring will be conducted no more than 10 minutes apart while bedside PG is 90 mg/dL and no more than 5 minutes apart when bedside PG is <90 mg/dL.

activities.name: Study Treatment Administration
activities.description: Study Treatment Administration. Once bedside PG reaches <60 mg/dL, the insulin infusion is stopped and approximately 5 minutes later study drug is administered. Indicates Time = 0 min.

activities.name: Injection-Site Assessment
activities.description: Injection-Site Assessment. Injection-site assessment for IMG only.

activities.name: Nasal Inspection
activities.description: Nasal Inspection. Nasal inspection both for IMG and LY900018.

activities.name: Vital Signs (Supine Blood Pressure, Pulse Rate, and Body Temperature)
activities.description: Vital Signs (Supine Blood Pressure, Pulse Rate, and Body Temperature). Time points may be added for each period if warranted and agreed upon between Lilly and the investigator. Predose time point will be between insulin infusion stop and study treatment.

activities.name: Single 12-lead ECG (Local)
activities.description: Single 12-lead ECG (Local)

activities.name: Triplicate 12-lead ECG (Central)
activities.description: Triplicate 12-lead ECG (Central). Time points may be added for Period 1 and Period 2 if warranted and agreed upon between Lilly and the investigator. Predose time point will be between insulin infusion stop and study treatment.

activities.name: Clinical Serology Tests
activities.description: Clinical Serology Tests. See Appendix 2, Clinical Laboratory Tests, for details.

activities.name: Clinical Lab Tests (Hematology, Clinical Chemistry, and Urinalysis)
activities.description: Clinical Lab Tests (Hematology, Clinical Chemistry, and Urinalysis). See Appendix 2, Clinical Laboratory Tests, for details. Patients do not need to fast for samples at screening or follow-up. At Periods 1 and 2, samples should be collected from patients who have fasted at least 8 hours before any study procedures.

activities.name: HbA1c
activities.description: HbA1c. See Appendix 2, Clinical Laboratory Tests, for details.

activities.name: Pregnancy Test (Female patients of childbearing potential only)
activities.description: Pregnancy Test (Female patients of childbearing potential only). Serum pregnancy test will be performed at screening. Urine pregnancy test will be performed at every admission period and follow-up visit if applicable.

activities.name: FSH (Female patients only)
activities.description: FSH (Female patients only). When needed to confirm postmenopausal status.

activities.name: Ethanol Testing
activities.description: Ethanol Testing. Additional tests can be done at the discretion of the investigator.

activities.name: Urine Drug Screen
activities.description: Urine Drug Screen. Additional tests can be done at the discretion of the investigator.

activities.name: PK (Glucagon)
activities.description: PK (Glucagon). Sampling times are relative to the time of study treatment administration (0 min). Predose time point will be between insulin infusion stop and study treatment.

activities.name: Plasma Glucose for PD
activities.description: Plasma Glucose for PD. -5 mins = stop insulin infusion. Sampling times are relative to the time of study treatment administration (0 min). Predose time point will be between insulin infusion stop and study treatment.

activities.name: Genetic Sample (Stored)
activities.description: Genetic Sample (Stored). Single sample for pharmacogenetic analysis taken prior to/on Period 1 Day -1.

activities.name: Anti-glucagon Antibodies
activities.description: Anti-glucagon Antibodies. In the event of drug hypersensitivity reactions (immediate or non-immediate), samples will be collected as close to event onset as possible, at event resolution, and 30 days following the event. Patients with TE ADA at follow-up/ED will undergo additional follow-up. Refer to Section 9.7.1 for details.

activities.name: Clarke Hypoglycemia Awareness Survey
activities.description: Clarke Hypoglycemia Awareness Survey

activities.name: Nasal and Non-nasal Score Questionnaire
activities.description: Nasal and Non-nasal Score Questionnaire. Sampling times are relative to the time of study treatment administration (0 min). Questionnaire will be collected in both LY900018 and IMG treatment groups in both periods.

activities.name: Edinburgh Hypoglycemia Scale: Experimental Hypoglycemia
activities.description: Edinburgh Hypoglycemia Scale: Experimental Hypoglycemia. Sampling times are relative to the time of study treatment administration (0 min). During hypoglycemia induction will be when PG 75 mg/dL. Predose time point will be between insulin infusion stop and study treatment.

notes.text: a Samples for immunogenicity, should be collected every 12 weeks (847 days) until the titer returns to baseline (ie, returns to within a single 2-fold dilution of the baseline titer) or until 1 year after the last dose of study treatment. A time-matched PK (glucagon) sample may be collected at the follow-up immunogenicity assessment(s) if warranted and agreed upon between both the investigator and sponsor.

Note: if multiple procedures take place at the same time point, the following order of the procedure should be used: ECG, vital signs, and venipuncture. Plasma glucose sample should be collected as close as possible of protocol-specified time point.

timings.name: Study Treatment Administration After Insulin Stop

conditions.name: Treatment Success Criteria
conditions.description: Primary efficacy endpoint for treatment success
conditions.text: Plasma glucose increase of 20 mg/dL from baseline within 30 minutes of glucagon administration without additional rescue therapy

conditions.name: Hypoglycemia Induction Target
conditions.description: Target plasma glucose level for hypoglycemia induction

conditions.name: Admission PG Criteria
conditions.description: Plasma glucose level required for admission on Day 1
conditions.text: PG level is 90 to 250 mg/dL on Day 1

conditions.name: TE ADA Resolution Criteria
conditions.description: Criteria for completing additional immunogenicity follow-up
conditions.text: Titer returns to baseline (within a single 2-fold dilution of the baseline titer)

conditions.name: Safety Review Criteria
conditions.description: Safety data review requirement before continuing enrollment
conditions.text: Safety data will be reviewed after the first 6 patients are administered LY900018 in Period 2

conditions.name: Evaluable Primary Outcome
conditions.text: At least 66 patients (at least 30 patients with T1DM and T2DM, respectively) complete both periods with evaluable primary outcome

transitionRules.name: Screening to Period 1 Transition
transitionRules.text: Patients will undergo a screening examination within 28 days prior to enrollment and be randomized to treatment sequence

transitionRules.name: Period 1 to Washout Transition
transitionRules.text: Patients complete Period 1 Day 1 procedures and may be discharged 6 hours after glucagon administration

transitionRules.name: Washout to Period 2 Transition
transitionRules.text: Periods 1 and 2 will be separated by a washout period of 3 to 14 days

transitionRules.name: Period 2 to Follow-up Transition
transitionRules.text: Patients will return for a follow-up visit 26 to 30 days after the last study treatment

transitionRules.name: Insulin Infusion Stop Trigger
transitionRules.text: Insulin infusion is stopped once bedside PG is <60 mg/dL

transitionRules.name: Admission Reschedule
transitionRules.text: Admission can be rescheduled if PG level is not 90 to 250 mg/dL on Day 1

transitionRules.name: Discontinuation for Other Study Enrollment
transitionRules.text: Enrollment in any other clinical study involving an investigational product or enrollment in any other type of medical research judged not to be scientifically or medically compatible with this study

transitionRules.name: Discontinuation for Medical/Safety/Regulatory Reasons
transitionRules.text: Participation in the study needs to be stopped for medical, safety, regulatory, or other reasons consistent with applicable laws, regulations, and good clinical practice

transitionRules.name: Investigator Decision Discontinuation
transitionRules.text: The investigator decides that the patient should be discontinued from the study for any reason

transitionRules.name: Patient Decision Discontinuation
transitionRules.text: The patient, or legal representative, requests to be withdrawn from the study

transitionRules.name: TE ADA Additional Follow-up Trigger
transitionRules.text: Patients with TE ADA at follow-up/ED will undergo additional follow-up every 12 weeks until titer returns to baseline or until 1 year after the last dose

transitionRules.name: Rescue Therapy for Insufficient Response
transitionRules.text: Procedures for Insufficient Response to Glucagon Administration

transitionRules.name: Inadvertently Enrolled Patient Continuation
transitionRules.text: If the sponsor or investigator identifies a patient who did not meet enrollment criteria and was inadvertently enrolled, a discussion must occur between the Lilly CP/CRP and the investigator to determine if the patient may continue in the study

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Completion
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Completion of both treatment periods and follow-up visit 26 to 30 days after the last study treatment

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Early Discontinuation - Other Study Enrollment
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Enrollment in any other clinical study involving an investigational product

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Early Discontinuation - Medical/Safety/Regulatory
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Participation stopped for medical, safety, regulatory, or other reasons

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Early Discontinuation - Investigator Decision
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Investigator decides patient should be discontinued for any reason

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Early Discontinuation - Patient Decision
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Patient or legal representative requests withdrawal from the study

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Lost to Follow-up
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Patient repeatedly fails to return for scheduled visits and is unable to be contacted by the study site

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Termination for Safety
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Following the review of the safety data from the first 6 patients to complete Period 2 Day 1, the study will be stopped if deemed necessary for patient safety

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Patient Replacement
scheduleTimelineExits.description: If patients discontinue from the study before completion of both periods with evaluable primary outcome for any reason, the patient may be replaced up to 75 patients enrolled
